President Jacob Zuma was on Friday rushed off stage after stormy weather caused the tent in which he was addressing a crowd on the Day of Reconciliation in North West to collapse. According to a video posted by the SABC, the president was about to wrap up his address when people who were sitting at the back started panicking about the storm that was about to uproot the tent. ALSO READ: Zuma&#8217;s Reconciliation Day speech halted as tent collapses Minutes later, the tent was uprooted and stayed in the air for two to three minutes, according to the SABC. The president&#8217;s security personnel then rushed to escort Zuma off stage. Proceedings were cancelled. No injuries have been reported yet. Watch the video below: Commenting on the &#8220;terrifying&#8221; incident, Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) deputy president Floyd Shivambu said it was the &#8220;gods&#8221; of the country who were refusing to be addressed by the president. &#8220;The gods of South Africa&#8217;s democracy &amp; reconciliation (*without justice) are refusing to be addressed by a criminal on #ReconciliationDay.&#8221; #reconciliationday #zuma #reconciliationdayrally When even Mother Nature hands you an L pic.twitter.com/BuIapvHhaA &mdash; Tumi Sole (@tumisole) December 16, 2016 For more news your way, follow The Citizen on Facebook and Twitter.